  <h1>Fibermaxxing for Men Over 40:<br><span class="accent">What's Real, What's Hype</span></h1>
  <p class="hero-sub">97% of men don't hit their daily fiber target. If you're running a high-protein diet heavy on chicken, beef, and eggs — and skipping the fiber-rich foods — your gut is probably paying the price. Here's the honest breakdown.</p>
  <p class="hero-meta">By Robert · May 9, 2026 · 8 min read</p>
</header>

<main>

  <div class="quick-answer">
    <h2>The Short Answer</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Fibermaxxing is trending — but the underlying problem it's solving is real:</strong> 97% of American men don't hit their daily fiber target, and most have no idea</li>
      <li>Men under 50 need <strong>38g of fiber per day</strong>. Men over 50 need 30g. The average man gets 10–15g. High-protein dieters often get even less</li>
      <li>Protein doesn't cause constipation — but <strong>high-protein diets crowd out the fiber-rich foods</strong> that keep digestion moving. That's the actual problem</li>
      <li>The 1990s fiber hype was partly overblown — fiber isn't a magic cure and some claims didn't hold up. <strong>The truth is in the middle:</strong> fiber matters, but source and gradual increase matter more than raw grams</li>
      <li>A 2021 Imperial College London study found <strong>higher fiber intake was directly associated with greater skeletal muscle mass and grip strength</strong> in adults over 40. This isn't just a gut issue</li>
      <li>You don't need to overhaul your diet — <strong>two or three targeted additions to what you're already eating</strong> closes most of the gap</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

