  <p>I'll be honest: I hadn't been paying much attention to fiber. I've been focused on protein — hitting my daily target, distributing it across meals, making sure the overnight window is covered. And for most of that time, I had decent digestion without thinking much about it, so fiber just wasn't on my radar.</p>

  <p>Then the fibermaxxing trend started showing up everywhere, and my honest first reaction was skepticism. I grew up in the era of the high-fiber 90s — the oat bran craze, the Burkitt hypothesis that high-fiber diets prevented colon cancer, the push to eat more bran cereal. And I knew that a lot of those specific claims didn't pan out in the clinical research. So I had assumed fiber was one of those things that got oversold and then quietly corrected.</p>

  <p>Turns out the truth is more nuanced. The 90s claims were partly overblown. But the underlying problem — that most men, especially men running high-protein diets, are chronically under-eating fiber — is very real. And the consequences go beyond digestion in ways I didn't expect.</p>

  <p>Here's what I found when I actually looked at the research.</p>

