  <p>The reduction after 50 reflects lower overall calorie intake — the fiber target is partially calorie-dependent. For men over 50, 30g is achievable without dramatic dietary changes if you're adding fiber-rich foods intentionally to what you're already eating. The key word is <em>intentionally</em> — it won't happen by accident on a high-protein diet.</p>

  <h2>The Muscle Connection Most Men Miss</h2>

  <p>Here's the part that changed how I thought about this. In 2021, researchers at Imperial College London analyzed dietary data from 6,454 adults aged 40 and older from the US National Health and Nutrition Examination Survey. They found that <strong>higher dietary fiber intake was directly associated with greater skeletal muscle mass and grip strength</strong> — independent of protein intake.</p>

  <p>Fiber doesn't build muscle directly. But it supports the gut microbiome, and the gut microbiome affects a remarkable number of systems that matter for muscle maintenance after 40: protein absorption efficiency, inflammation levels, insulin sensitivity, and short-chain fatty acid production (which has downstream effects on muscle metabolism).</p>

  <p>Men running high-protein diets who are simultaneously running a fiber deficit are potentially limiting how effectively their protein actually converts to maintained muscle mass. The protein is coming in. The microbiome environment that helps process and absorb it is running on empty.</p>

  <p>This connects directly to the <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/anabolic-resistance-after-40/">anabolic resistance</a> conversation — the reduced muscle sensitivity to protein signals that develops after 40. Chronic gut inflammation from a disrupted microbiome is one of the contributing factors to anabolic resistance. Fiber is part of what keeps that inflammation in check.</p>

  <h2>Myth vs. Fact: The Fiber Claims Worth Knowing</h2>

  <div class="mvf-stack">
    <div class="mvf-card">
      <div class="mvf-myth">
        <div class="mvf-tag">Myth</div>
        <p><strong>Fiber prevents colon cancer.</strong> This was the big 90s claim. Large RCTs did not find significant colorectal cancer prevention from high-fiber diets in people who already had polyps. Observational data suggested a benefit; intervention data was much weaker.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="mvf-fact">
        <div class="mvf-tag">Fact</div>
        <p><strong>Fiber supports gut microbiome health and reduces systemic inflammation</strong> — which has broader benefits for metabolic and cardiovascular health. The cancer-prevention story was oversold. The gut health story is solid.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="mvf-card">
      <div class="mvf-myth">
        <div class="mvf-tag">Myth</div>
        <p><strong>More fiber always fixes constipation.</strong> For people with slow gut transit, adding insoluble fiber can actually worsen constipation by adding bulk to stool that isn't moving. Some studies show improvement after fiber reduction.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="mvf-fact">
        <div class="mvf-tag">Fact</div>
        <p><strong>Soluble fiber — oats, legumes, fruit — generally supports regularity. Insoluble fiber is more variable.</strong> The type and source matter. Gradually increasing fiber from whole foods rarely causes the problems that sudden supplementation does.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="mvf-card">
      <div class="mvf-myth">
        <div class="mvf-tag">Myth</div>
        <p><strong>You don't need fiber on a carnivore or high-protein diet.</strong> Some people tolerate very low fiber diets without obvious gut symptoms. But "no symptoms" isn't the same as an optimal gut microbiome or optimal metabolic health.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="mvf-fact">
        <div class="mvf-tag">Fact</div>
        <p><strong>The gut microbiome requires prebiotic fiber to maintain diversity and short-chain fatty acid production.</strong> Low diversity microbiomes are associated with higher inflammation and worse metabolic outcomes over time — even without obvious digestive symptoms.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="mvf-card">
      <div class="mvf-myth">
        <div class="mvf-tag">Myth</div>
        <p><strong>High protein causes constipation.</strong> Protein itself is not the culprit and won't directly cause constipation in people eating enough fiber alongside it.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="mvf-fact">
        <div class="mvf-tag">Fact</div>
        <p><strong>High-protein diets crowd out fiber-rich foods, and it's the fiber deficit that causes the gut issues.</strong> The fix is adding fiber back alongside the protein — not reducing protein. Lentils, for example, deliver both 18g protein AND 15g fiber per cup.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="mvf-card">
      <div class="mvf-myth">
        <div class="mvf-tag">Myth</div>
        <p><strong>Fibermaxxing means eating 60–70g of fiber per day.</strong> The trend term implies extreme maximization, and some TikTok content pushes unrealistically high targets that cause bloating and gut distress.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="mvf-fact">
        <div class="mvf-tag">Fact</div>
        <p><strong>The actual target is 30–38g depending on your age — and most men starting from 10–15g should increase gradually over 4–6 weeks.</strong> Jumping fiber intake dramatically causes bloating and gas as the microbiome adjusts. Slow and steady is the right approach.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

