  <h2>A Practical Starting Point — Not a Diet Overhaul</h2>

  <p>The goal is not to rebuild your diet from scratch. The protein strategy that's already working stays in place. What you're adding is a fiber layer on top of it. Here's how to do that without bloating, without major preparation burden, and without disrupting protein targets:</p>

  <div class="plan-box">
    <h3>Closing the Fiber Gap Without Disrupting Your Protein Strategy</h3>
    <div class="plan-item">
      <div class="plan-num">1</div>
      <div class="plan-text"><strong>Start slow — add 5g of fiber per week, not 25g overnight.</strong> The gut microbiome needs time to adjust. Going from 10g to 38g in one week almost guarantees bloating, gas, and discomfort that makes you quit. Add one fiber-rich food per day for the first week, then expand.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="plan-item">
      <div class="plan-num">2</div>
      <div class="plan-text"><strong>Add chia seeds to your morning protein.</strong> Two tablespoons mixed into Greek yogurt or cottage cheese adds 10g of fiber, a few grams of protein, and requires zero extra prep. This single change closes roughly 25–30% of the daily gap for most men.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="plan-item">
      <div class="plan-num">3</div>
      <div class="plan-text"><strong>Replace one animal-protein snack per week with lentils or edamame.</strong> A cup of lentils delivers 15g fiber AND 18g protein — it doesn't reduce your protein target at all. Edamame gives you 8g fiber and 17g protein from the freezer in 5 minutes. These are dual-purpose foods that fit your existing goals.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="plan-item">
      <div class="plan-num">4</div>
      <div class="plan-text"><strong>Add a vegetable to every dinner, every time.</strong> A cup of broccoli, spinach, or mixed greens adds 3–5g of fiber. Four nights a week that's 12–20g of additional fiber — just from the side that was probably missing. Steam it. Done in five minutes.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="plan-item">
      <div class="plan-num">5</div>
      <div class="plan-text"><strong>Drink more water as you increase fiber.</strong> Fiber needs water to do its job — without it, increasing fiber intake can paradoxically worsen constipation. For every 10g of fiber you add, aim for an additional 8–12 oz of water. This is where most men fall short when increasing fiber.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>The Bottom Line on Fibermaxxing</h2>

  <p>The trend name is a little ridiculous. But the problem it's pointing at is real, the science behind the gut-muscle connection is solid, and the practical fix is far simpler than most men expect.</p>

  <p>You don't need a fiber supplement. You don't need to overhaul a diet that's working for protein. You need two or three targeted additions to what you're already eating, introduced gradually, with enough water to support the change.</p>

  <p>Men over 40 focused on <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/sarcopenia-men-over-40/">sarcopenia prevention</a> and muscle maintenance have every reason to care about fiber — not because it builds muscle, but because it supports the gut environment that determines how effectively the protein you're already tracking actually works. <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/sleep-muscle-loss-after-40/">Sleep, protein, and recovery</a> are the main levers. The fiber gap is the one most men running high-protein diets are unknowingly leaving open.</p>

  <p>Close it gradually. Your gut — and the muscle you're working to keep — will notice.</p>

